About
Get lost in one of the most charming neighborhoods in Paris, brimming with unique boutiques and stylish art galleries. Besides its vibrant LGBTQIA+ community, Le Marais also has a rich Jewish heritage, with winding streets lined with historic medieval architecture. If you're looking for a night out, head to one of the many gay bars or clubs that the area is known for. Take a walking tour to discover fascinating insights about the neighborhood, or a food tour to have a taste of the area's vibrant culinary scene—travelers say the falafel is some of the best! Visit during the week for fewer crowds and wear comfortable walking shoes to navigate the neighborhood's cobblestone streets. – Tripadvisor

One of the Top 5 Iconic site in Paris
Sep 2024 • Solo
Le Marais has become a trendy district of the Marais. Definitely Iconic like the Latin Quarter and La Rive Gauche, as its graffitis sometimes prove it.
It is located in the 4th arrondissement. It is full of museums, trendy boutiques, galleries and bars, some of which are gay.
It also used to contain the Jewish quarter of the city. This district is still home to many kosher restaurants.
Another iconic site is the Place des Vosges, verdant, which houses elegant arcades and the Victor Hugo museum, where the writer lived.
The streets around the Saint-Paul metro station lead to the Maison Européenne de la Photographie but you have not less intersting museums such as Les Archives Nationales and Le Musee Carnavalet, ideal for rainy days.

But actually if we forget the trendy aspect of the Marais, I love it for its narrow streets and its Louis XIII architecture which takes me back to the history of Paris.
Written October 29, 2024

Charming area of the Right Bank to explore in Paris
Aug 2024 • Couples
This is a charming district on the Right Bank in central Paris. There are quieter neighbourhoods you can stroll as well as important sightseeing including several museums, churches and historic hotels, Opera house, quaint public squares and monuments to enjoy.

You will also find a nice range of hotels and dining opportunities, all nicely connected to the rest of the city by buses and the Metro. It is a really nice location of Paris to spend a day or more exploring, even longer if you plan to stay overnight in this area of the city.

Pro con advice- my visit to the swamp
Mar 2024 • Solo
PROS
* Famous historical district in a central location
* Old Jewish Quarter with a few still intact synagogues and a few kosher eateries and two kosher bakeries
* Now notable for busy nightlife and liberal lifestyles
* Some cultural stuff such as Centre Pompidou and Museum of the Shoah
* Many restaurants bars and party venues

CONS
Busy crowded and noisy with party people at night

"I VISITED THIS PLACE'...
... because I have stayed here before and liked it very much. I wanted to be close to some Jewish stuff, including food eateries, which I didn't do very much. As a matter of fact, I only ate at Chlew; the other places were too busy, uninteresting or not open- the bakeries are listed as opening at 0830H!!

WAS IT WORTH THE COST?
Yes

WOULD "I VISIT THIS PLACE" AGAIN?
Yes

ADVICE
A good place to visit but beware of the evening crowds, even on weekday nights

Philippe B
Paris, France
247 contributions
Hi. The Marais is a really old area, mostly left undisturbed by develoment. So hotels are few, and mostly very chic period accomodations. So either go AirB&B, or stay for example in the 9th arondssement. Many nice hotels (relatively speaking of course) in the price range you indicate. It could be fun to pick one in one of the "passages", if they have availalbility. But beware, they usually don't have restaurants. And from there you can reach the Marais in a short metro ride. Conversely, you can do the same by selecting the Bastille area on the other side. More hip and culturally diverse, within a short walk of the Marais. Have fun!
